This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

MINOR FLOODING CONTINUING AT BANDIANA

Minor flooding is continuing along the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is currently at 2.78 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is expected to remain below the minor flood level (3.30 m) during Monday.

The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.85 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Kiewa River at Bandiana is likely to remain above the minor flood level (2.80 m) during Monday and into Tuesday.

No significant rainfall was recorded across the Kiewa River catchment for the 24 hours to 9:00 am Monday. No significant rainfall is forecast for the next few days.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream

  • The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging 0 mm in the upper part of the catchment as well as in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Sunday 08 October 2023. 
  • Rainfall totals of less than 1 mm is forecast for the catchment for Monday 09 October 2023.
  • Water levels at various locations in the upper part of the Yarra River are receding, only the lower part of the Yarra River is still rising in response to the rain event.

Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream:
  • The level of the Yarra River at Coldstream is currently at 4.21 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (4.00 metres) and falling slowly. 
  • It is expected to drop below the Minor Flood Level (4.00 metres) tonight, Monday 9th October.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 

  • Minor flooding in the Yarra catchment is expected to affect low-lying areas adjacent to the waterway including bicycle paths.

This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 10/10/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Community Information message is being issued for Briagolong, Cobbannah, Culloden, Fernbank, Glenaladale, Hunter Corner, Iguana Creek, Lindenow South, Moornapa, Munro, Stockdale, Walpa, Woodglen and surrounding areas.

  • The bushfire at Duffy Rd, Briagolong is not yet under control.
  • Recent rain has dampened fire activity. However, there is still active fire within the area as logs and trees continue to burn.
  • You may see isolated pockets of flames and smoke over the burnt area.
  • Firefighters are monitoring the area.
  • Several roads are still closed due to active fire and hazardous trees.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures.
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.

Community Meetings are planned for the following areas;

Tuesday 10/10/23 - Valencia Creek Hall at 5:30pm

Tuesday 10/10/23 - Briagolong Hall at 7:30pm

Wednesday 11/10/23 - Glenaladale Recreation Reserve at 7:00pm 
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 11/10/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON, SEYMOUR AND SHEPPARTON

Goulburn Murray Water has advised the releases from Lake Eildon are likely to remain around 17,000 ML/d during for the remainder of Monday and into Tuesday.

No significant rainfall has been observed since 9:00 am Sunday. No significant rainfall is forecast for the next few days.

The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 9.61 metres and falling slowly, with minor flooding. The Goulburn River at Shepparton is likely to remain above the minor flood level (9.50 m) Monday afternoon. The river level may fall below the minor flood level (9.50 m) overnight Monday into Tuesday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Some local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Watt Road and Raftery Road Shepparton start to flood at 8.75m.
  • Watts Road, between McClennan Street and Old Tip Road has been closed due to floodwater. 
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 10/10/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON AND SEYMOUR

Goulburn Murray Water has advised the releases from Lake Eildon are likely to remain around 17,000 ML/d during for the remainder of Monday and into Tuesday.

No significant rainfall has been observed since 9:00 am Sunday. No significant rainfall is forecast for the next few days.

Minor flooding is continuing along the Goulburn River from downsteam Lake Eildon to Seymour. Minor flooding is continuing at Trawool.

The Goulburn River downstream Lake Eildon is currently at 3.45 metres and steady, with minor flooding. Based on Goulburn Murray Water's planned releases from Lake Eildon, the Goulburn River downstream Lake Eildon is likely to remain above the minor flood level (3.00 metres) for the remainder of Monday and into Tuesday.

The Goulburn River at Seymour is currently at 4.03 metres and falling, with minor flooding. The Goulburn River at Seymour is likely to remain above the minor flood level (3.80 m) for the remainder of Monday and into Tuesday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock, pumps and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
Eildon to Seymour: At Minor flood level 3.8 m on the Seymour Gauge:

This Community Information message is being issued for Dutson Downs, Golden Beach, Goon Nure, Hollands Landing, Lake Wellington, Loch Sport, Meerlieu, Ocean Grange, Paradise Beach, Seacombe, Banksia Peninsula. 

  • Firefighters are working on several hot spots, clearing debris around the fire affected area and removing any identified hazardous trees. 
  • Please obey all traffic management signage and directions and slow down to 40 km per hour when passing emergency vehicles.  This is for your own safety and for the safety of our firefighter.
  • Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads.
  • Recent rainfall has assisted with fire suppression, however communities need to remain aware of fires near them and monitor changes in conditions. 
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 11/10/2023 12:20 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
Minor Flood Warning for the Latrobe River Issued at 11:18pm on Monday 9 October 2023. Flood warning number 8

Minor flooding to continue at Rosedale for the next few days 
  • No significant rainfall has been recorded in the 24 hours to 9 am Monday in the Latrobe catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the next few days.

Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon:
  • Minor flooding is continuing along the Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon.
  • The Latrobe River at Rosedale (Main Stream) is currently at 4.33 metres and steady, above the minor floodlevel (4.00 m). The Latrobe River at Rosedale (Main Stream) is likely to remain above the minor flood level for the next few days.
This is an update, replacing the Advice message issued at 15:26pm on October 8 2023.

Flood Safety Advice:

SES advises that all community members should:
  • Never walk, ride or drive through floodwater, Never allow children to play in floodwater, Stay away from waterways and stormwater drains during and after heavy rain.
  • Keep well clear of fallen power lines
  • Be aware that in fire affected areas, rainfall run-off into waterways may contain debris such as ash, soil, trees and rocks, and heavy rainfall increases the potential for landslides and debris across roads. 

Current Emergency Information is available at
http://emergency.vic.gov.au 
For emergency assistance contact the SES on 132 500.
Current Road and Traffic Information is available at the VicTraffic website: http://traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/ Next Issue:
The next warning will be issued by 11:30 am EDT on Monday 09 October 2023.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Dont swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 11/10/2023 12:30 pm or as the situation changes.

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

  • The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging 0 mm in the upper part of the catchment as well as in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Sunday 08 October 2023. 
  • Rainfall totals of less than 1 mm is forecast for the catchment for Monday 09 October 2023.
  • Water levels at various locations in the upper part of the Yarra River are receding, only the lower part of the Yarra River is still rising in response to the rain event.

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
Impacts in your area:

  • Minor flooding in the Yarra catchment is expected to affect low-lying areas adjacent to the waterway including bicycle paths.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 10/10/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.
